snippet.textDisplay: i agree with what you said about the amount of superpower-y teen shows because honestly, i don’t like them. i know a lot of people enjoy superpowers and heros and villains in their shows or movies and i totally understand that, but it’s really not my thing, and it seems like it’s mostly what’s out there right now for my demographic (high schoolers) other than teen high school romcoms/dramas. which im also tired of. i’d already fell in love with the original books as a kid, and i feel like anne with an e is the grown up version, and it’s come exactly when i’d love it most. it’s darkness is realistic, it’s not tacky, and it’s not sickly sweet. im actually surprised that they canceled it because of the 25-54 age range issue, because i’d imagine if someone read the books as a kid, no matter how old they were, they would be at least intrigued by the show. i’m really sad they canceled it. hopefully they will listen to all the people rooting for it, as the casting, the cinematography, the costumes, and the acting are all fantastic.

snippet.textDisplay: People who say Anne with an E is boring are probably using their last braincells to figure out the tremendous depths of the progressive and door-opening non-profit non-baiting CW TV show/teen drama Riverdale which should have been canceled after its second season, because let's be honest it lost it's appeal and is nothing more than bad writing and shitty character development and an immensely increasing amount of plot-holes and Cheryl has ultimately went coucou-bananas, but let us cancel the one great show that is shedding some light into social issues such as feminism, sexism, sexual harassment etc. Seriously, I would rather have my children watch Anne with an E than Riverdale or any other show that is claimed acceptable for a teenage audience. I hate this world for not being able to see the beauty behind this show. Deeply saddened. But you know what, you do you.
